EASTERN EQUINE ENCEPHALITIS - USA (13): (MICHIGAN, MARYLAND), EQUINE
********************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: 15 Aug 2013
Source: Wood TV.com [edited]
http://www.woodtv.com/news/local/sw-mich/mare-dies-from-equine-encephalitis


This year's [2013] 1st case of eastern equine encephalitis (EEE) has been confirmed in Van Buren County, according to the Michigan Department of Agriculture and Rural Development (MDARD). A state veterinarian confirmed the case in a 12-year-old mare on Thursday [15 Aug 2013]. That mare experienced stumbling, depression and blindness as her brain swelled, causing her to die.

The horse had not been vaccinated against EEE, which the state recommends. EEE causes swelling of the brain. It's rare and spread by the bite of an infected mosquito. Most people infected have no apparent illness. Severe cases of EEE begin with the sudden onset of headache, high fever, chills and vomiting, according to the Centers for Disease and Control and Prevention. The illness may then progress into disorientation, seizures or coma. There is no specific treatment for EEE; care is based on symptoms.

EEE is rare in humans. The last known [human] cases in Michigan were in 2010, with 2 in Kalamazoo County and one in Barry County. All 3 people survived. There was only one case of EEE in Michigan last year [2012]. That was in a puppy in Van Buren County.

Southwest Michigan -- including Barry, Calhoun, Cass, Kalamazoo, St. Joseph and Van Buren counties -- typically has a higher concentration of EEE than the rest of the state, according to the MDARD.

